observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Government:
thru the Office of the Municipal Accountant, reconcile their records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to identify the employees whose GSIS,            Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth contributions or loan amortizations were still not remitted and effect the immediate remittance thereof;
thru the Agency Authorized Officer to report to the GSIS the updated list of all of its employees, their corresponding employment status, positions, salaries and such other pertinent information, including subsequent changes therein, if any, as required under Section 6.a of the IRR of R.A. No. 8291; and
require the employee/s concerned to observe the remittance of mandatory contributions within the prescribed period to avoid payment of penalties and/or surcharges.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
adopt measures to intensify tax collection and invest in revenue-generating projects or activities to increase the Municipality’s income to be able to accommodate higher PS cost without exceeding the PS Limitation;
require the Municipal Budget Officer to strictly observe the limitation over the PS cost set forth under Section 325(a) of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 6.3.6 of LBC No. 98 and henceforth, refrain from providing additional PS expenditures until such time that the PS cap is observed;
enjoin the HRMO to limit the hiring of additional employees if their services are not crucial to the LGU;
direct the Municipal Accountant to post the correct amount of the CNA Incentive in the books of accounts to reflect the correct balance of the Government Equity account and see to it that all bonuses and incentives granted by the LGU to its employees are properly recorded in the prescribed accounts provided in the guidelines;
enjoin the HRMO and the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor and review the details incorporated in the payroll and henceforth, ensure that the amounts encoded therein are accurate and reliable; and
require Ms. Pearlita Durano and Ms. Noelle Katrina Molo to refund the overpaid salaries (net of mandatory contributions) amounting to ₱24,853.99 and ₱22,801.79, respectively.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
the BAC to explain the noted deficiencies and lapses in the conduct of above procurement of infrastructure projects and submit all lacking bid documents to the Audit Team;
the BAC and contractor to use the prescribed standard forms incorporated in the GPPB Circular No. 04-2020 dated September 16, 2020;
the Municipal Accountant to see to it that all payments for infrastructure projects are completely supported with documentary requirements as required in COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and submit to the Audit Team the above-noted lacking documents; and
the Municipal Engineer to submit to the Audit Team the documents with deficiencies enumerated in Annex J and lacking documents on the grant of time extension to Speed Touch Construction and to comply with the guidelines set forth under Item 11 of Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in granting requests for time extensions.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

 direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their respective records and henceforth comply with Sections 12, 30, 31 and 32 of GAM for LGUs in preparing the SL and Cashbook;




Moreover, enjoin the Municipal Accountant to consider the PAJE relative to the book reconciling items and present fairly the Cash in Bank account in the financial statements; 




Further, instruct the Accountant to make sure that the bank statements are stamped as received and indicated with date of receipt thereof; and


 Finally, should there be bank accounts that to date have no copy yet of monthly bank statements, send a letter to the depository banks requesting copies therefor.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

 reconcile the accounts Due to NGAs and Trust Liability – DRRMF;

 submit the updated SL and Report on Fund Utilization of the BGCM;




 substantiate the eight adjusting journal entries in Annex H with supporting documents, schedules, computation and analysis and submit the same to the audit team; and



 consider the PAJE in order to present fairly the Due to NGAs account in the FS.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor through the Municipal Accountant to:

  refrain from granting cash advance to those officers and employees with outstanding balance;



 enforce the immediate settlement or liquidation of all outstanding cash advances particularly for those aged more than 30 days to more than five years;

 employ internal controls such as issuance of memorandum or demand letter to delinquent officers and employees who have accounts that already due on bordering the deadline of 30-days; and

 reconcile the balances reported in the FS, SL and RUCA and ensure always that these reports are fairly presented.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the

 MGSO and the Municipal Accountant to comply with the process in storing, release, and recording of inventories as provided for in Section 121 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume II;

  Moreover, require the Municipal Accountant to update his records and ensure henceforth that all inventories are properly accounted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

  require the Municipal Engineer to estimate the useful life of the infrastructure assets and the Municipal Accountant to provide allowance for depreciation thereof;


 enjoin the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile thoroughly the results of the physical count with the accounting records;


 require the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Assessor (for the land account) to conduct a complete physical count of all PPEs and submit the RPCPPE on time; and

 require the Municipal Accountant to prepare SL for all PPE accounts and reconcile them with the GL and FS.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

 instruct the Municipal Engineer and MPDC to implement the projects funded by the Development Fund for CY 2020 including those new PPAs funded through realignment and update the Audit Team of its status;

 require the Municipal Engineer to disclose all government infrastructure projects in the quarterly Report of Government PPAs and submit the same to the Audit Team on time in compliance with Item 2 of COA Circular No. 2013-004;

 direct the MPDC to facilitate the adequate planning and budgeting of developmental projects and consider to refrain from inputting lump sum or generic term appropriation as it will need separate approval from the sanggunian; and

 provide copies of SB Resolution to the Audit Team for the PPAs funded out by the lump sum or generic term appropriation that had been identified by the 21 barangays and implemented already during the year.

We therefore recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

 instruct the GFPS to properly accomplish the GPB and GAR in accordance with Items 4.1.C.4.1.a, 4.1.C.4.1.e, Annex D and Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 dated January 12, 2016;

 direct the GFPS TWG to revise the GAD Accomplishment Report, review and approve its corresponding narrative reports and submit the same to the Audit Team and DILG;

 enjoin the GFPS to observe timely submission of the GAR and its HGDG PIMME Checklist including its supporting reportorial contents; and

 allow the GFPS to attend capacity-building or training on how to administer or accomplish the GAD-related tools such as but not limited to the HGDG Checklist and GMEF Questionnaire.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

 instruct the Municipal Treasurer to adopt strategies in intensifying the collection of real property tax such as information campaign to encourage taxpayers to take advantage of early payment discount;

 require the Municipal Treasurer and Accountant to reconcile their records and present the correct amount of tax delinquencies; 

 require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the year-end balances of RPT and SET Receivables and Deferred RPT and SET accounts and adjust the GL and FS for the unrecorded collections; and

 require the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the Provincial Assessor in the conduct of tax mapping to update the real property units and their corresponding assessed value within the municipality.

We recommended that the: 

(a) 	Provincial Governor, in behalf of the concerned persons liable therefor, secure approval from the COA for settlement of audit disallowances in installment basis pursuant to COA Resolution No. 2015-031; 

(b) 	Provincial Accountant (i) require the concerned persons liable to settle in full and/or installment, as the case may be, the audit disallowances pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-006; and (ii) support recorded disallowances with updated subsidiary ledgers/records and/or schedule containing proper disclosure on the reference NFD, persons liable and amount; and

We recommended that the Provincial Engineer:

(a) institute appropriate measures/action to address the causes of the delay in the completion of the projects; 



(b) cause the imposition of liquidated damages on the noted delay of completion of the two projects; and

We recommended that the GFPS Executive Committee:

(a) prioritize the monitoring of implementation of GAD-related PPAs to ensure full implementation of the PPAs included in the GPB pursuant to Item 5.b.iv of Section 4.1A of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01; 

(b) monitor the implementation of the PPAs and ensure the attainment of the objectives of every PPA that would address the identified gender issues; 

(c) constantly make a follow-up or set a specific period of the submission of other concerned government agencies of the required sex-disaggregated data and other GAD – related information to update the GAD existing database to have an effective basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

(d) undertake a thorough gender analysis based on gathered relevant data for proper identification of the critical and relevant gender issues to ensure that the approved PPAs to be incorporated in the succeeding GPBs are responsive to address the same, pursuant to Section B (1) of the JMC No. 2013-01; and 

(e) facilitate the preparation of the GAD AR and furnish the Audit Team a copy thereof.

We recommended that the Provincial Engineer, being the officer-in-charge in the implementation of the PGR’s infrastructure projects: 

(a) 	conduct inspection and monitoring of the unfinished projects and determine the cause/s of the delay of implementation; 

(b) 	compel the concerned contractors to adopt stringent measures to expedite the completion of the unfinished/on-going projects; 

(c) 	for the succeeding infrastructure projects, conduct detailed engineering activities prior to implementation thereof to ensure that there will be no hindrances in their completion within the contracted duration; and

(d) 	submit a list of projects which were not completed within the contracted duration with their corresponding contractors to the Provincial Accountant with the advice to impose liquidated damages to the concerned contractors.

With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct the Municipal Engineer and MPDC to implement the projects funded by the Development Fund for CY 2020 including those new PPAs funded through realignment and update the Audit Team of its status;
require the Municipal Engineer to disclose all government infrastructure projects in the quarterly Report of Government PPAs and submit the same to the Audit Team on time in compliance with Item 2 of COA Circular No. 2013-004;
direct the MPDC to facilitate the adequate planning and budgeting of developmental projects and consider to refrain from inputting lump sum or generic term appropriation as it will need separate approval from the sanggunian; and
provide copies of SB Resolution to the Audit Team for the PPAs funded out by the lump sum or generic term appropriation that had been identified by the 21 barangays and implemented already during the year.

We therefore recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct the GFPS to properly accomplish the GPB and GAR in accordance with Items 4.1.C.4.1.a, 4.1.C.4.1.e, Annex D and Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 dated January 12, 2016;

b)  direct the GFPS TWG to revise the GAD Accomplishment Report, review and approve its corresponding narrative reports and submit the same to the Audit Team and DILG;

c)  enjoin the GFPS to observe timely submission of the GAR and its HGDG PIMME Checklist including its supporting reportorial contents; and

d) allow the GFPS to attend capacity-building or training on how to administer or accomplish the GAD-related tools such as but not limited to the HGDG Checklist and GMEF Questionnaire.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding cash advances;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to make sure that previous cash advances are liquidated first before granting of new cash advances;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to strengthen internal control by complying with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in granting cash advance and the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in resorting to alternative mode of procurement.
